Mental awareness is now a thing. With Nigerian artiste Banky. W sharing the Nigerian suicide hotlines on his social media page to Falz encouraging depression victims to speak up in his tweet, Nigerians are admitting that depression is not just a Western illness. Understanding Depression photo credit Ebony Magazine According to the National Institute of Mental Health, depression (major depressive disorder or clinical depression) is a common but serious mood disorder that causes severe symptoms which can affect how you feel, think, and handle daily activities, such as sleeping, eating, or working. To be diagnosed with depression, the symptoms must be present for at least two weeks. Often described as a dark and deep pit that one could fall into at certain stages in life, victims are constantly advised to speak up to professionals or experienced people when feeling down. As suicide rates among celebrities and masses alike increase, it is clear that depression is a respecter of no age, gender, race, or status. With the personal and societal expectation to achieve certain achievements in life, an average Nigerian is prone to get depressed in certain life phases. Beyond professional help, here are five tips that may help you or your loved ones: Depression group therapy photo credit kouƒçing